canonical:
  title: 祭廣陵公文 代人行
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 云云溫溫我公宗室羽儀一行一步罔蹈匪彝愛客接士畦畛莫施輔以文章河憲是追兼精藥餌如大老醫以博濟而爲任凡幾活於傷痍妙極丹靑如宿畫師手自摹其佛像常嚮仰之毋疲有過兮己自當有善兮人之推考公行爲天若相之胡不畀年遽促大期嗚呼哀哉九天隔兮鸞馭遠百日周兮隙駟馳骨寧可朽兮名不隳兮行潦之薦維以寓悲
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 祭廣陵公文 代人行
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 云云。溫溫我公。宗室羽儀。一行一步。罔蹈匪彝。愛客接士。畦畛莫施。輔以文章。河憲是追。兼精藥餌。如大老醫。以博濟而爲任。凡幾活於傷痍。妙極丹靑。如宿畫師。手自摹其佛像。常嚮仰之毋疲。有過兮己自當。有善兮人之推。考公行爲。天若相之。胡不畀年。遽促大期。嗚呼哀哉。九天隔兮鸞馭遠。百日周兮隙駟馳。骨寧可朽兮。名不隳兮。行潦之薦。維以寓悲。
korean:
  title: 광릉공에게 제사 지내는 글 어떤 사람 대신 행하다
  author: 이규보
  language: kor
  text: 온화한 우리 공이여, 왕실의 봉황이로다. 한 번 행하고 한 번 걷는 것이 도가 아니면 밟지 않고, 손님을 사랑하고 선비를 접대함에 간격을 두지 않도다. 또 문장을 잘하여 하간헌왕(河間獻王)과 대등하였도다. 겸하여 의약에 정밀하니, 노련한 의사와 같아서 널리 구제함을 소임으로 가지고 있었으니 얼마나 많은 사람을 살렸겠는가. 단청(丹靑)을 잘 그려서 노련한 화사(畫師)와 같아 손으로 스스로 부처의 화상을 그려 놓고는 항상 우러러보고 있었도다. 허물은 자신이 맡고 착한 것은 남에게 미루었다. 공의 행위를 볼 때 하늘이 도와줄 것 같은데 어찌 수명을 주지 아니하고 문득 대기(大期 죽을 시기)를 재촉하는가. 슬프다 구천(九天)은 막히고 신선[鸞馭]은 멀구나. 어느덧 백일(百日)이 돌아오니 세월이 빠르도다. 뼈는 비록 썩을지언정 이름은 없어지지 않을 것이다. 허술한 음식으로 오직 슬픔에 부칩니다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1120_010_0190&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: A Sacrificial Rite for the Duke of Guangling, Performed on Another's Behalf
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: Gentle and temperate was our Duke—a phoenix among the royal household. Each step, each movement tread only upon virtue's path, never straying from the Way. In welcoming guests and receiving scholars, he knew no distance or reserve. His mastery of letters rivaled the great Han princes; his scholarship flowed like rivers of wisdom. Yet more remarkable still—he mastered the healing arts with such precision that he moved like an experienced physician, and through his broad compassion, how many suffering souls did he not restore to health? In painting too he excelled, his brush rivaling the masters of old. With his own hand he rendered the Buddha's image, and there he would stand, gazing upward in reverence. The faults he claimed as his own; the virtues he attributed to others. Looking upon his deeds, one might think Heaven itself would favor him—why then did it not grant him length of years? Why did it hasten his appointed end? Alas, the Nine Heavens are shuttered, and the celestial chariots recede into distance. One hundred days have wheeled round, and time gallops swift as coursing steeds. Though bone may crumble into dust, his name shall never fade. With this meager offering, we commit our sorrow to remembrance.
  footnotes:
    - The Nine Heavens (九天) refers to the celestial realm in Chinese cosmology; the celestial chariots (鸞馭) evoke immortal spirits departing from the earthly world.
    - The reference to the hundred days marks the traditional mourning period in East Asian ritual practice.
